      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "It&#39;s not entirely correct to say that <code>Integer::min</code> implements <code>Comparable</code>. It is not a type that can implement anything. But it is evaluated into an object which implements <code>Comparable</code>."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 295869,
        "reputation" : 75003,
        "user_id" : 600500,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 54,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5925786f174975db18cbc83dd85e5c1d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Paŭlo Ebermann",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/600500/pa%c5%adlo-ebermann"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 2,
      "creation_date" : 1509008848,
      "post_id" : 22561687,
      "comment_id" : 80847396,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "<code>Comparator&lt;Integer&gt;</code> is a single-abstract-method (aka &quot;functional&quot;) interface, and <code>Integer::min</code> fulfills its contract, so the lambda can be interpreted as this. I don&#39;t know how you see BinaryOperator coming into play here (or IntBinaryOperator, either) – there is no subtyping relationship between that and Comparator."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2347441,
      "reputation" : 69769,
