  "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/22561614/why-do-maxintegermax-and-minintegermin-compile-on-a-java-8-stream",
  "title" : "Why do .max(Integer::max) and .min(Integer::min) compile on a Java 8 Stream?",
  "body" : "<p>See the following code, which originates from a now-deleted Stack Overflow question:</p>\n<pre><code>final List&lt;Integer&gt; list \n    = IntStream.rangeClosed(1, 20).boxed().collect(Collectors.toList());\n\nSystem.out.println(list.stream().max(Integer::max).get());\nSystem.out.println(list.stream().min(Integer::min).get());\n</code></pre>\n<p><em>(note: I do know that this code won't &quot;work&quot; and that <code>Integer::compare</code> should be used — I just extracted it from the linked question)</em></p>\n<p>According to the Javadoc of <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/Stream.html#min-java.util.Comparator-\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>.min()</code></a> and <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/Stream.html#max-java.util.Comparator-\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>.max()</code></a>, the argument of both should be a <code>Comparator</code>. Yet here the method references are to static methods of the <a href=\"http://download.java.net/jdk8/docs/api/java/lang/Integer.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>Integer</code></a> class.</p>\n<p>Why does this compile at all?</p>\n"
}